    <title>Combined summary - Proposed alternatives to the 20MB step</title>
    <updated>2023-06-09T22:02:12.598978+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-June/008417.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>There is controversy among Bitcoin core developers regarding a proposal to raise capacity in the ecosystem. While some see it as necessary for growth, others believe that it compromises long-term security for short-term user experience. Decentralization is at the core of Bitcoin's security model, and there are concerns that increasing the block size limit from 1MB to 20MB could lead to centralization.Andresen's proposal to increase the block size limit to 20MB has been met with skepticism from Jérôme and other core developers who believe that the focus should be on finding solutions for scaling without compromising decentralization. They suggest that small incremental improvements should be made instead of making big changes to ensure that the network remains decentralized.The urgency to do something about the block size limit is seen as a fallacy since there are promising solutions such as Layer 2 and off-chain solutions available. However, implementing these solutions may not be effective as it would require a lot of effort and be technically risky. Additionally, new solutions may constantly emerge, making it difficult to keep up with the ever-changing landscape.The value of Bitcoin is also discussed, with some believing that decentralization is the primary objective, while others believe that usage is what gives Bitcoin value. The discussion around decentralization leads to a debate about the absolute number of independent people in control, rather than the percentage of the community that mines. Ultimately, the discussion highlights the political nature of Bitcoin and the need for all groups, including businesses and end-users, to be in consensus about the goals of Bitcoin.The debate over scalability and decentralization continues to be a contentious issue within the Bitcoin community, with no clear consensus on the best way forward. It is important for all stakeholders in the Bitcoin ecosystem to come together to find solutions that balance both scalability and decentralization to ensure that Bitcoin remains secure and valuable in the long term.</summary>
